text: In the 1992 regular legislative session, the General Assembly passed and Governor Brereton Jones signed
label: BODY

text: Senate Bill 63 (codified as KRS 11A), the Executive Branch Code of Ethics, which states, in part:
label: BODY

text: No present or former public servant shall, within six (6) months of following termination of his office or
label: BODY

text: employment, accept employment, compensation or other economic benefit from any person or business
label: BODY

text: that contracts or does business with the state in matters in which he was directly involved during his
label: BODY

text: tenure.  This provision shall not prohibit an individual from returning to the same business, firm,
label: BODY

text: occupation, or profession in which he was involved prior to taking office or beginning his term of
label: BODY

text: employment, provided that, for a period of six (6) months, he personally refrains from working on any
label: BODY

text: matter in which he was directly involved in state government.  This subsection shall not prohibit the
label: BODY

text: performance of ministerial functions, including, but not limited to, filing tax returns, filing applications
label: BODY

text: for permits or licenses, or filing incorporation papers.
label: BODY

text: A former public servant shall not represent a person in a matter before a state agency in which the
label: BODY

text: former public servant was directly involved, for a period of one (1) year after the latter of:
label: BODY

text: a) The date of leaving office or termination of employment; or
label: BODY

text: b) The date the term of office expires to which the public servant was elected.
label: BODY

text: This law is intended to promote public confidence in the integrity of state government and to declare as public
label: BODY

text: policy the idea that state employees should view their work as a public trust and not as a way to obtain private
label: BODY

text: If you have worked for the executive branch of state government within the past six months, you may be subject
label: BODY

text: to the law's prohibitions.  The law's applicability may be different if you hold elected office or are
label: BODY

text: contemplating representation of another before a state agency.
label: BODY

text: Also, if you are affiliated with a firm which does business with the state and which employs former state
label: BODY

text: executive-branch employees, you should be aware that the law may apply to them.
